Unable to resist the temptation, my classmates flock to such pristine and well located streams like metal-eating fish around a bloated carcass. Back in the day, we used to call it a "land fee." And like emperors bent on maintaining an unassailable barrier around their orb, little was ever done to curb this menace. As time went on and the muscles on my back hardened from hauling bamboo baskets bulging with waste out of manholes ("don't even think about recycling that," the office men at the loading bays would say, "especially if it's your first trip"), the hope of changing the system seemed lost, reluctantly falling to exhaustion.

This was until I took to a world I had only known through my camera, through books, television and the cinema; a world that was less a delta than a tidal wave of ubiquitous refuse. Over the years the images that have impressed me most were not the beautiful vistas of pristine landscapes, but the trash-stained surfaces, the subtle human acts (and struggles) commemorated by our waste.
